ife in the light of rapidly changing political mores and the growing importance of the press in public life. The scientific journal did not arise as a natural solution to the problem of communicating scientific discoveries. Rather, as Csiszar shows, its dominance was a hard-won compromise born of political exigencies, shifting epistemic values, intellectual property debates, and the demands of commerce. Many of the tensions and problems that plague scholarly publishing today are rooted in these tangled beginnings. As we seek to make sense of our own moment of intense experimentation in publishing platforms, peer review, and information curation, Csiszar argues powerfully that a better understanding of the journal's past will be crucial to imagining future forms for the expression and organization of knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCommunication in science. 0aSciencexPeriodicalsxPublishingxHistoryy19th century. 0aTechnical writingxHistoryy19th century. 4aBritain. 4aFrance. 4aexpertise. 4ainformation. 4aintellectual property. 4aopen science. 4apeer review. 4apolitics. 4ascholarly publishing. 4ascientific authorship. 70(DE-601)1057660460(DE-588)4121932-6aWissenschaftliche Zeitschrift2gnd 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226553375423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226553375.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles